# Contributing

Thanks for wanting to contribute to this cheatsheets repository! This document gives a short, practical guide for reporting issues, proposing changes, and submitting pull requests.

## Quick summary
- Open an issue for bugs or feature requests.
- Fork the repo and create a branch for your change.
- Make small, focused commits with clear messages.
- Submit a pull request with a descriptive title and summary.

## Reporting issues
- Search existing issues first to avoid duplicates.
- When opening a new issue, include:
	- A short, descriptive title.
	- Steps to reproduce (if applicable).
	- Expected vs actual behavior.
	- Relevant file paths or snippets.

## Making changes
- Fork the repository and create a topic branch from `main` (or the default branch):
	- Use a short branch name describing the change, e.g. `fix/mips-typo` or `add/ma1522-formulas`.
- Keep changes small and focused. One logical change per branch/PR makes review easier.
- Update or add documentation where appropriate.

## Submitting a pull request
- Push your branch to your fork and open a PR against the repository's default branch.
- In the PR description, explain:
	- What you changed and why.
	- Any files that reviewers should focus on.
	- How to preview or verify the change locally (if applicable).
- Link related issues with `Fixes #<issue-number>` when the PR resolves an issue.

## Coding style and content
- Follow the existing repository structure and naming conventions.
- Keep formatting consistent with surrounding files. If the project uses a formatter or build tool, run it before submitting.
- Prefer clear prose and concise commit messages. Example commit message format:
	- `feat: short description for mips` — e.g. `fix: register table typo`

## Tests and verification
- If your change requires verification (build, preview, rendering), include brief instructions in the PR so reviewers can reproduce the results.

## License and ownership
- By contributing, you agree that your contributions will be licensed under this repository's license (see `LICENSE`).

## Contact
- If you're unsure about the best way to contribute, open an issue or contact the maintainers via the repository's issue tracker.

Thanks — contributions keep this project useful and up to date!
